# Authorship & Attribution

## Commit Messages

- **NEVER include AI model names** in commit messages (e.g., "Claude Sonnet 4.6", "GPT-4")
- **NEVER add `Co-Authored-By: AI` footers** (e.g., `Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet <noreply@anthropic.com>`)
- Commits are authored by the human developer
- AI assistance is implicit in the development process

### ✅ Correct
```
feat(backend): add rate limiting to convert endpoint
```

### ❌ Wrong
```
feat(backend): add rate limiting to convert endpoint

Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>
```

## Pull Request Descriptions

- Use plain, professional language
- Focus on **what** was changed and **why**
- Avoid mentioning AI tools, models, or assistants
- Do not include AI attribution or model credits

### ✅ Correct PR Summary
```
## Summary
Added persistent rate limiting via Supabase conversions table
to replace the in-memory dictionary implementation.
```

### ❌ Wrong PR Summary
```
## Summary
Used Claude Sonnet to refactor rate limiting...
Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code)
```

## Documentation & Code Comments

- Comments and docs should be authored-neutral
- Avoid mentioning AI tools or models
- Example: `// Handle edge case` instead of `// Claude suggested handling this edge case`

## Team Communication

When discussing implementation internally:
- Focus on technical decisions and trade-offs
- Mention tools/processes objectively if relevant (e.g., "used automated testing")
- Omit AI model names from discussions
